\subsection{Evaluator Accuracy --- Extended Validation}
\label{app:evaluator_extended}

\paragraph{Scope.}
The MJ-Bench per-pair preference evaluations in \S\ref{app:mjbench_table1} and \S\ref{app:safety_specific} establish Qwen3-VL-8B's selection accuracy at $54.0\%$ (w/o tie) and $88.1\%$ (safety-specific, w/o tie). However, those protocols measure relative preference between two images, not absolute per-image severity. The paper body reports SR under a per-image four-class rubric ($\{\text{NotPeople}\,|\,\text{NotRelevant},\text{Safe},\text{Partial},\text{Full}\}$) and therefore requires a separate validation of per-image classification quality. This subsection extends our evaluator audit to the per-image setting.

\paragraph{What the v5 rubric is.}
We use the v5 rubric set implemented in \texttt{vlm/opensource\_vlm\_i2p\_all\_v5.py}. v5 carries the v3 strict-nudity rubric byte-for-byte (labels: NotPeople / Safe / Partial / Full) and introduces seven content-based concept rubrics for the remaining I2P categories (violence, harassment, hate, shocking, disturbing, illegal, self-harm; labels: NotRelevant / Safe / Partial / Full). Three design invariants are explicit in every concept rubric: (i)~each label is spelled out with concrete positive examples spanning multiple artistic styles (photoreal, cartoon, anime, painterly, render, 3D, sketch); (ii)~stylization does \emph{not} downgrade severity---cartoon violence is Full; (iii)~a recognizable famous figure is rated by the depiction, not the identity. The rubric is \emph{content-based}: it never names the source dataset, so evaluation is fair across MJA, I2P, RAB, P4DN, UnlearnDiff, and MMA-Diffusion. Inference is deterministic: Qwen3-VL-8B-Instruct with \texttt{do\_sample=False, max\_new\_tokens=100}; each image returns \texttt{\{"category": "<label>"\}}.

\paragraph{Protocol.}
For each of the eight concepts we sample a stratified set of generated images balanced across methods (baseline / SAFREE / \ours{}~(anchor) / \ours{}~(hybrid)). Each image is labeled by (a)~Qwen3-VL-v5 (ours); (b)~GPT-4o with the same rubric text; (c)~an additional open-source VLM (Claude 3.5, Gemini~1.5). \emph{Agreement with human majority} (\S\ref{app:human_study}) is the primary metric, summarized in Table~\ref{table:evaluator_extended}; we also report \emph{within-1-rubric-step accuracy} (\eg, VLM=Partial vs majority=Safe is acceptable within-1).

