\paragraph{Why VLM rather than NudeNet/Q16 (ported from prior workshop).}
Earlier safety-in-diffusion studies scored nudity with NudeNet~\citep{notai_nudenet_2019} or with embedding-based safety classifiers. Two failure modes motivated the move to a VLM protocol, which we adopt here following the earlier workshop benchmark of~\citet{kil2026ascg}. \emph{(1) Over-sensitivity.} NudeNet's binary classification flags socially acceptable exposure (swimwear, athletic attire, partial clothing) as full nudity, producing false positives that incentivize over-suppression. Under the four-class VLM rubric these cases are assigned to Safe or Partial. \emph{(2) Semantic-collapse confound.} Aggressive safety interventions can degrade generations into artifacts, blur, or noise; NudeNet then fails to detect unsafe content because \emph{nothing} is detectable, so the destroyed image is implicitly counted as Safe. The VLM rubric's NotRelevant label (NotPeople for nudity) explicitly captures semantic collapse, preventing this inflation. The same classifier-based Full%-on-MMA-style NudeNet numbers that a reader may be familiar with from the prior literature are reported separately for reference in \S\ref{app:mma_nudenet}.

\paragraph{Verification notes for the skeptical reader.}
The v5 module imports v4's prompts as a base and only overwrites the seven I2P keys, so the nudity rubric is byte-for-byte identical to v3/v4. Output filenames are suffixed \texttt{\_v5.json} / \texttt{\_v5.txt} to prevent overwriting v3 results. Greedy decoding + explicit JSON-only response format yields deterministic top-1 labels across runs.

\subsection{Human Agreement Study}
\label{app:human_study}

\paragraph{Purpose.}
Establish direct human-vs-VLM agreement on a focused subset to strengthen the claim that Qwen3-VL-v5 is a reliable judge for the paper's SR reporting.

\paragraph{Protocol.}
\emph{Annotator pool.} Approximately 20 adult annotators recruited under content-warning consent, English-literate (rubric is in English), task-compensated. Annotators may opt out at any time. \emph{Stimuli.} For each of the eight concepts, we sample $\sim\!20$ images from the I2P top-60 evaluation set, balanced across method (baseline / SAFREE / \ours{}-anchor / \ours{}-hybrid) and across rubric classes where possible, yielding $\sim\!160$ images per annotator (or a stratified subset). \emph{Task.} Each annotator classifies each image into one of $\{\text{Full},\text{Partial},\text{Safe},\text{NotRel (or NotPeople for nudity)}\}$ using a one-paragraph compressed version of the v5 rubric (\S\ref{app:evaluator_extended}). Forced choice, no skip option. \emph{Ground truth.} Majority vote among three annotators per image (three-way ties are broken by a fourth annotator or dropped). \emph{Inter-annotator agreement.} Pairwise Cohen's~$\kappa$ (averaged) and multi-annotator Fleiss'~$\kappa$; these define the \emph{ceiling}---the VLM cannot be expected to exceed human consistency. \emph{VLM agreement.} For each image, Qwen3-VL-v5 vs majority: exact-match agreement and within-1-rubric-step accuracy (\eg, VLM=Partial / majority=Safe counts within-1; VLM=Full / majority=Safe is a full error). Table~\ref{table:human_study} reports these metrics per concept.

